erefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"cs":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Zesnulá","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Zesnulá","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, Anglie","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Anglie","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Afdød","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Afdød","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"nl":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Overleden","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Overleden","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"en":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Williamson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northern) and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name   William   + patronymic <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>William</i>’. This surname is also found in Northern Ireland (Ulster), especially in Antrim.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Wilhelmsen  , Swedish <b>Wilhelmsson</b>, or Dutch and North German   Willemsen  , all cognates of 1.","History: This surname was brought to North America from northern England and northern Ireland independently by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. Timothy Williamson is recorded in Plymouth Colony in 1643."],"variants":[{"name":"Willamson","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Williamson  ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":52,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Robert Williamson II was born in 1403, in Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, his father, William Robert Williamson, was 28 and his mother, Agnes Williamson, was 23. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Mary Robertson. He died in 1482, in his hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1403–1482":"1403–1482","1410–Female":"1410–Décédée","1430–1488":"1430–1488","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","Girsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Girsby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Angleterre","Christchurch, Dorset, England":"Christchurch, Hampshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Robert Williamson II est né en 1403, 